The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, April 19: The Centre collected Rs 3.75 lakh crore from direct taxes last fiscal, missing the revised target by Rs 12,000 crore. The collection from corporate income tax and personal income tax, however, was 13.1 per cent up from the 2008-09 level, finance ministry sources said.                            
	 Calcutta, April 19: Pitney Bowes, the worlds largest provider of mail room equipment and software, plans to launch digital franking machines equipped with remote resetting technology in India by June, said K. M. Nanaiah, managing director of Pitney Bowes India.                            
	 New Delhi, April 19: The Petroleum amp; Natural Gas Regulatory Board has approved a provisional tariff of Rs 52.23 per million British thermal unit that Mukesh Ambani-owned East-West pipeline will charge to transport gas from Reliance Industries KG-D6 fields to users.                             
	 New Delhi, April 19: The corporate affairs ministry has told the Rajya Sabha that companies can pay higher salaries to the top brasses after getting an approval from the government under the provisions of the Companies Act of 1956.                            
	 New Delhi, April 19: The Supreme Court today declined to grant bail to Price Waterhouse auditor Subramani Gopalakrishnan, involved in the Satyam fraud. However, he was permitted to renew his bail application because of a delay by the CBI in filing the third chargesheet.                             
	 New Delhi, April 19: Indian Oil Corporation has completed the expansion of its Haldia refinery to 7.5 million tonnes (mt) from 6mt.                             
	 New Delhi, April 19: The price of pan-India 3G spectrum rose to Rs 6,068 crore on the eighth day of the auction and the bidding is still going strong. The price hike ensures a minimum of Rs 24,620 crore for the governments kitty.
                                                                                                                                
